article.description: Vladimir Radmanovic nearly outscored the  Miami Heat in the fourth quarter as the Seattle SuperSonics rolled to a 100-71 victory.
article.headline: 'No-heart' Heat no match for well-rested Sonics
article.linkText: 'No-heart' Heat no match for well-rested Sonics
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle SuperSonics used their two days off to rest and heal up.
Payton

They looked plenty healthy against the Miami Heat. Gary Payton overcame a sore foot and scored 18 points in the SuperSonics' 100-71 victory over the struggling Heat on Saturday night. "Our guys were fresher, and it showed,'' Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "We still have some things to work on.'' Payton, who shot 8-of-11 from the field and added 11 assists, had X-rays on his right foot that were negative Friday night. He was coming off a 40-point performance in loss to Indiana on Wednesday and overcame the pain in his foot. "The days off helped,'' McMillan said. The All-Star guard was not available for comment after the game, but McMillan was happy with how his team responded to their recent heartbreaking 114-111 overtime loss to the Pacers. "We want to try and start a win streak,'' said McMillan, whose team is about to embark on a nine-day, five-game road trip. "You know we've won a game here and there, but we need to be consistent with our effort and challenge ourselves on this road trip.'' Vladimir Radmanovich came off the bench to score 19 points, including 5-of-5 from 3-point range in the fourth quarter for Seattle. Desmond Mason added 14, and Rashard Lewis had 13. The Heat were led by Rasual Butler, who scored a career-high 19 points off the bench. Eddie House had 14, and Mike James and Caron Butler added 12 apiece. But it wasn't nearly enough as the Heat shot 30.2 percent, worse than the 38.4 percent they shot the previous night in Portland. "We have no collective heart right now,'' said Heat coach Pat Riley, whose team was beaten 88-69 by the Trailblazers on Friday. "We've gotten our heads handed to us two nights in a row. We have not been able to overcome their tremendous starts.'' Tempers flared the entire game as eight technical fouls were called. The Sonics, which were coming off a heartbreaking overtime loss to Indiana on Wednesday, jumped out to a quick start. Seattle led 16-0 over the first four minutes and took a 34-12 lead at the end of the first quarter. It was the second straight night in which Miami got off to a horrendous start. "At the start, it seemed like it was layup, layup, layup,'' said Eddie Jones, who had only five points on 1-of-8 shooting for Miami. "When that happens, it just crushes you. We tried to make some adjustments, but then they started hitting from the outside. It was frustrating.'' The closest Miami could get in the second half was 15 points. With 6:24 to play, Lewis was fouled hard on a fastbreak by Travis Best, who was whistled for an intentional foul. Lewis and Best went chest-to-nose before the two started pushing and shoving. Both players went to the floor in the melee, but no punches were thrown. A lot of the players got involved, and Pat Riley stepped in to help calm the situation. Both players received technicals. "It was a hard foul and then he got in my face,'' said Best, who is 11 inches shorter than the 6-foot-10 Lewis. "I don't know what he was trying to do. I just wanted to make sure he didn't make a layup and let them know that they won't be dunking all night.'' The Heat didn't score until Eddie House hit a 21-foot jumper with 7:31 to play in the first quarter. He had just come off the bench after a disgusted Riley called timeout with his team trailing 16-0.

Game notes
he SuperSonics are 14-1 at home against the Heat. ... Vladimir Stepania was ejected late in the third quarter when he received his second technical foul. ... Before the game, Riley said he was considering making a change to the starting lineup of Malik Allen, Caron Butler, Brian Grant, Best and Eddie Jones. The Heat are 4-10 with that lineup. ... The Heat have scored 80 points or less in nine games this season. ... Rasual Butler reached double-digits in scoring for the first time since Nov. 16 against Washington.
